Anatomy of a deployment manifest.

A deployment looks almost identical to a replica set. The same replicas, the same selector, the same template. Plus a few fields that govern how the controller updates pods. Let us go through them.

Replicas is the same target count you saw on the replica set. The deployment simply passes it through to the active replica set.

The selector's match labels must match the template's labels, just like before. But here is a key difference. Once set, the selector is immutable on a deployment. You cannot change it after creation. That rule exists to avoid the orphaned pods problem.

The template is the pod template, and this is the field you will change most often, usually to bump an image. Any change inside the template triggers a rollout.

Then come the update controls. The strategy type is either rolling update, the default gradual replacement, or recreate, which kills all then starts all. We will cover both shortly.

Inside the rolling update settings are two knobs. Max surge is how many extra pods the controller may create above the target during a rollout. Twenty five percent of four replicas means one extra pod. Max unavailable is how many of the desired pods may be unavailable at the same time during a rollout. Again, twenty five percent of four means one.

A few more fields round it out. Revision history limit caps how many old replica sets are kept for rollback. Min ready seconds makes a new pod wait, after becoming ready, before it counts as available. And progress deadline seconds is how long a stuck rollout waits before it is marked failed. Together these fields turn a plain count of pods into a safe, reversible release process.
